# Adding sub-plots
x = np.arange(1, 11)
y1 = 2 * x
y2 = 3 * x

plt.subplot(1, 2, 1) # (1, 2, 1) : 1 row 2 column and last 1 means first plot figure.
plt.plot(x, y, color='g', linestyle='-')

plt.subplot(1,2,2) # 1 row , 2 col and 2 subplot fig (matrix stuff).
plt.plot(y1, y2, color='r')
plt.show()

Box plot¶

  • sometimes boxplots are called "box and whisker" plots
  • line in the box is the median, 50% of the data is above the median, and 50% of the data is below the median.
  • within the box itself, we have 25% of the data above teh median, and 25% of the data below the median. so 50% data within the box.
In [146]:

  • dl_applied:
  • The DuckworthLewisStern method (DLS) is a mathematical formulation designed to calculate the target score (number of runs needed to win) for the team batting second in a limited overs cricket match interrupted by weather or other circumstances.
  • The method was devised by two English statisticians, Frank Duckworth and Tony Lewis, and was formerly known as the DuckworthLewis method (D/L)

  • win by runs: won by first batting
